  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Swaziland Crafts Industry Development Programme</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Ongoing drought in Swaziland has led to 40% of the population receiving food aid in recent years with agriculture alone no longer providing families with an adequate income. The situation is exacerbated by the highest HIV/AIDS prevalence rate in the world. Growing demand from the tourist sector and regional markets for high quality, fair trade handcrafts offers a unique opportunity to improve poor people&#x2019;s incomes, particularly for the most vulnerable (85% of whom are women). However, the sector has relatively few sustainable handcraft organisations and the majority are not Swazi-led, even though the businesses run on fair trade principles. This project will work with Swaziland&#x2019;s most promising handcraft groups to develop a network of genuinely local fair trade businesses. By building the capacity of handcraft producer groups, creating a national network of these groups, and establishing access to international markets, it will improve the livelihoods of producers and their families, in particular women. The majority of the businesses will be Swazi-led to change the racial profile of the existing business model. The creation of a strong handcraft sector will support a future generation of children which will lose many of its parents to HIV/AIDS. Workplace training on HIV/AIDS will raise awareness and provide education to handcraft producers and workers.</narrative>
  </description>
